{"source_key":"sha256-c8597aca71664a84bdd657ea13dadbd3","record_index":1241,"record_hash":"sha256:9a1e19a539a53f1cf35d4bd0cf49e817a30bdc62124a5819e94a973e558346f9","timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:26:21.686Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"{\"previous_status\":{\"completed\":\"**Highest-Priority Changes**\\n\\n1. **Make review sharing privacy first-class, not a later question.**  \\n   The doc explicitly targets review sharing, then punts access controls to “Later Questions.” That’s too risky. Add a v1 share/export policy now: who can see transcripts, which record kinds are included, whether tool calls/files/env snapshots are redacted, and whether automatic matches are only private suggestions until explicitly shared.\\n\\n2. **Add read APIs beyond the two facades.**  \\n   `getSessionTimeline(session_key, window?)` and `findRelatedSessions(target)` are too thin. You also need:\\n   - `listSessions(project, filters, cursor)` for handoff discovery\\n   - `getHandoffBundle(session_key, cursor/window, include_env?)`\\n   - `getRelatedSessionDetail(target, session_key, turn_window, redaction_policy)`\\n   - `previewReviewShare(target)` before anything leaves repo-private scope  \\n   Review sharing especially needs hydration controls, pagination, redaction level, and “expand around highlighted turns.”\\n\\n3. **Fix the retry/enrichment lifecycle hole.**  \\n   The rule “create a turn only when new records are written” is good, but it creates a nasty edge case: if transcript records write and environment snapshot fails, a retry sees zero new records and cannot improve the turn. Same for commits made after the last stop hook. Add an explicit way to enrich/update an existing turn’s environment snapshot, or store a separate observation/enrichment object.\\n\\n4. **Don’t launch without lifecycle/status fields.**  \\n   Sessions and sources need `last_captured_at`, `capture_status`, `source_status`, `last_error_kind`, `is_live/stale`, maybe `ended_at`. Handoff needs to know whether this is current enough to trust. Review sharing needs to know whether evidence is stale, partial, or from a dead transcript source.\\n\\n5. **The environment snapshot is probably too heavy.**  \\n   Capturing up to 100 commits per branch with up to 256 paths each, on every stop ho\n[TRUNCATED]\n branches, or PR retargets. Add branch head OID, base/merge-base OID where available, stack/branch IDs where GitButler has them, and review head/base identity. Otherwise old observations will look more authoritative than they are.\\n\\n7. **Index staleness needs a minimum v1 cleanup story.**  \\n   “No deletion or rebuild in v1” is too casual. Verification prevents false truth, but stale indexes still cause ghost candidates, sync bloat, and privacy headaches after deletion/redaction. At least define tombstones or a rebuild/prune command before implementation.\\n\\n8. **Backfill as one capture turn is bad for handoff UX.**  \\n   It’s fine for storage truth, but handoff needs readable provider-level groups. Store or derive provider turn/display groups strongly enough that a backfilled session is not one giant blob with one fake-ish environment timestamp.\\n\\n9. **Scoring needs edge-case guards before product behavior.**  \\n   File overlap is noisy: lockfiles, READMEs, generated files, broad renames, shared config, and monorepo hot paths will overmatch. Add path weighting/exclusions, recency decay, broad-change downranking, max candidate limits, and support for “matched over several later turns,” not only previous-to-current.\\n\\n10. **Automatic high-confidence display is fine privately, risky externally.**  \\n   “No required human confirmation” is okay inside a repo-local/private UI. For review sharing, automatic association should produce a draft suggestion, not publish transcript evidence to reviewers by default. The product line should be: automatic discovery, explicit sharing.\\n\\n**Net Judgment**\\n\\nThe core idea is solid: persist observations, not ownership. But before implementation, tighten the API/read contract, add lifecycle/enrichment semantics, and make privacy/export scope part of v1. The current storage model is thoughtful, but it risks being simultaneously heavy in GitMeta and under-specified where the product will actually get scary: sharing, staleness, retries, and explainable reads.\"}}","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:26:21.686Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}